  • \(P(\text{Apple OS} | \text{Desktop}) = .3\)

Recall

We used the properties of probabilities to uncover the joint distribution.

\[ P(A = a,\ B = b) = P(B = b)\, P(A = a\, |\, B = b)\\ P(A = a,\ B = b) = P(A = a)\, P(B = b\, |\, A = a) \]

\[ P(A = a) = \sum_{\begin{array}{c}j\ =\ \text{all}\\ \text{values} \\ \text{of B}\end{array}} P(A = a \text{ and } B = j)\] \[ P(A = a) = \sum_{\begin{array}{c}j\ =\ \text{all}\\ \text{values} \\ \text{of B}\end{array}} P(B = j)\,P(A = a | B = j)\]

Uncovering the joint distribution

Uncovering the joint distribution allows one to:

  • Understand the relationship between outcomes \(A\) and \(B\)
  • Use information about \(B\) to predict \(A\) (or vica versa)

Univariate vs Bivariate

Univariate Bivariate
\(F_X(x) = P(X\leq x)\) \(F_{X,Y}(x,y) = P(X\leq x\ \text{and}\ Y\leq y)\)
\(f_X(x) = \frac{d}{dx} F_X(x)\) \(f_{X,Y}(x,y) = \frac{\partial^2}{\partial x \partial y} F_{X,Y}(x,y)\)

Covariance

A measure of linear association

\[ Cov(X,Y) = E[(X - E[X])(Y - E[y])]\]

Covariance

A measure of linear association

\[ Cov(X,Y) = E[XY] - E[X]E[Y]\]

Covariance

Sample covariance

\[ \widehat{Cov}(X,Y) = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N (X_i - \bar{X})(Y_i - \bar{Y}) \]

How might one generate a confidence interval for the covariance?

Related question: How might one generate the sampling distribution for the covariance?

How might one generate a confidence interval for the covariance?

Bootstrap

R <- 5000
out <- rep(NA, R)
for(i in 1:R){
  rows <- sample.int(nrow(sn), nrow(sn), replace = TRUE)
  new_sample <- sn[rows, ]
  out[i] <- cov(new_sample[,c("waist","tri")], use = "complete")[1,2]
}
quantile(out, c(0.05/2, 1-0.05/2))

How might one generate a confidence interval for the covariance?

Bootstrap

##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 57.18068 74.82760

How might one generate a confidence interval for the covariance?

Central Limit Theorem

\[ \widehat{Cov}(X,Y) = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N (X_i - \bar{X})(Y_i - \bar{Y}) \]

Are the observations independent?

How might one generate a confidence interval for the covariance?

Central Limit Theorem

Nobs <- sum(!is.na(sn$waist_centered_tri_centered))
sample_mean <- mean(sn$waist_centered_tri_centered, na.rm = TRUE)
sample_var <- var(sn$waist_centered_tri_centered, na.rm = TRUE)
sample_mean + qnorm(c(0.05/2, 1-0.05/2)) * sqrt(sample_var)/sqrt(Nobs)

How might one generate a confidence interval for the covariance?

Correlation

A standardized measure of linear association

\[\rho(X,Y) = Cor(X,Y) = \frac{Cov(X,Y)}{\sqrt{V[X]V[Y]}}\]

Correlation

A standardized measure of linear association

  • \(-1\leq \rho(X,Y)\leq 1\)
  • \(|\rho(X,Y)| = 1\) if and only if \(X\) and \(Y\) are exact linear functions of each other.

Example

Sample Correlation

\[ \hat{\rho}(X,Y) = \frac{\widehat{Cov}(X,Y)}{s_X\ s_Y} \]

Sample Correlation in R

cor(sn[,c("waist","tri")], use = "complete")
##           waist       tri
## waist 1.0000000 0.4979708
## tri   0.4979708 1.0000000

How might one generate a confidence interval for the correlation?

Central Limit Theorem

\[ \hat{\rho}(X,Y) = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{(X_i - \bar{X})}{s_X}\frac{(Y_i - \bar{Y})}{s_Y} \]

Are the observations independent?

How might one generate a confidence interval for the correlation?

Central Limit Theorem

sn_center_scaled <- scale(sn[,c("waist","tri")])
waist_tri_centered_scaled <- sn_center_scaled %>% apply(1,prod)
sample_mean <- mean(waist_tri_centered_scaled, na.rm = TRUE)
sample_var <- var(waist_tri_centered_scaled, na.rm = TRUE)
Nobs <- sum(!is.na(waist_tri_centered_scaled))

sample_mean + qnorm(c(0.05/2, 1-0.05/2)) * sqrt(sample_var)/sqrt(Nobs)
